What You Don’t Know Might Hurt You: Possible Dangers of Assuming A Fixed ICC Across Treatment Arms

DRAFT / WORK IN PROGRESS

Josh Nugent

# Load required packages, preprocess the data
library(tidyverse)
library(pander)
alpha_cost5000 <- readRDS("alpha_cost5000.rds")
dat_long <- alpha_cost5000 %>% gather(key = type, value = TIE, 3:5)

Defining our terms

In this document I’ll refer to the Type I error rate where the data analyst fits a model that does not allow for different ICCs across treatment arms as the “naive TIE rate”. Allowing for different ICCs by arm will be called the “flexible” approach.

Comparing naive and flexible, marginalizing over all ICC value combinations

First, here is all of the data for this run of 5000 simulations - various combinations of cluster size, number of clusters, and icc values by arm. Here you can see that the naive TIE rate is always greater than or equal to the flexible TIE rate.

ggplot(data = alpha_cost5000) +
  geom_point(aes(x = TIE_flexible, y = TIE_naive, color = as.factor(nsub), shape = as.factor(nclust))) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0) +
  labs(x = "Flexible TIE rate", y = "Naive TIE rate")

The shapes are a little hard to see, so let’s split them up by cluster size and number of clusters; see below. You can see that there is more variability in the top right corner of the grid where the number of clusters is small and the number of subjects per cluster is large. Further, when the number of subjects per cluster is small, NLME is somewhat conservative.

ggplot(data = alpha_cost5000) +
  geom_point(aes(x = TIE_flexible, y = TIE_naive, color = as.factor(nsub), shape = as.factor(nclust))) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = .05, color = "grey", linetype = "dotdash") + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = .05, color = "grey", linetype = "dotdash") + 
  labs(x = "Flexible TIE rate", y = "Naive TIE rate") +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(nsub), rows = vars(nclust), labeller = label_both) + theme(legend.position="none")

Examining naive method across different ICC combinations

First, one specific example: 10 subjects per cluster, 10 clusters per arm. ICC values are the rows and columns. This is the TIE for just the naive method.

table1 <- alpha_cost5000 %>% filter(nsub == 10, nclust == 10) %>%
  select(TIE_naive, icc1, icc2) %>%
  spread(icc1, TIE_naive) %>% 
  remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="icc2")
pander(table1)

A little hard to see what’s going on with just numbers. Let’s look at it as a heat map, again just the naive method:

ggplot(data = alpha_cost5000 %>% filter(nsub == 10, nclust == 10)) +
  geom_tile(aes(x = as.factor(icc1), y = as.factor(icc2), fill = TIE_naive)) +
  labs(title = "A single combination: 10 observations per cluster, 10 clusters per arm", x = "ICC1", y = "ICC2")

It seems that the error rate rises as cluster imbalance rises, which makes sense, but also rises as the ICC rises along the diagonal. Let’s look at that across all combinations again:

ggplot(data = alpha_cost5000) +
  geom_tile(aes(x = as.factor(icc1), y = as.factor(icc2), fill = TIE_naive)) +
  labs(title = "All # cluster / cluster size combinations", x = "ICC1", y = "ICC2") +
  facet_grid(cols = vars(nsub), rows = vars(nclust), labeller = label_both)

A little hard to see what the larger patterns are - it seems that the pattern discussed above is most obvious when the number of clusters is small and the number of subjects per cluster is large. We may want to run this with more simulations to see if the patterns become clearer.

Let’s look at the ‘marginal’ heat map above across all values of cluster size / # of clusters that we have - this is the mean of all of the heat map values in the above grid stacked.

margdata <- alpha_cost5000 %>% select(icc1, icc2, TIE_naive) %>% group_by(icc1, icc2) %>% summarise(mean(TIE_naive)) %>% ungroup %>% mutate(TIE_naive = `mean(TIE_naive)`) %>% select(-`mean(TIE_naive)`)
ggplot(data = margdata) +
  geom_tile(aes(x = as.factor(icc1), y = as.factor(icc2), fill = TIE_naive)) +
  labs(title = "Mean TIE of All # cluster / cluster size combinations", x = "ICC1", y = "ICC2") +
  scale_fill_gradient(limits = c(.025, .055))

It looks like the pattern we suspected is holding up.

Examining flexible method across different ICC combinations

Will switching to the flexible method improve the outcomes?

margdata2 <- alpha_cost5000 %>% select(icc1, icc2, TIE_flexible) %>% group_by(icc1, icc2) %>% summarise(mean(TIE_flexible)) %>% ungroup %>% mutate(TIE_flexible = `mean(TIE_flexible)`) %>% select(-`mean(TIE_flexible)`)
ggplot(data = margdata2) +
  geom_tile(aes(x = as.factor(icc1), y = as.factor(icc2), fill = TIE_flexible)) +
  labs(title = "All # cluster / cluster size combinations", x = "ICC1", y = "ICC2") +
  scale_fill_gradient(limits = c(.025, .055))

# The 'marginalized' naive TIE rate is always larger than the marginalized flexible TIE rate for matching ICC pairs.
margdata$TIE_naive > margdata2$TIE_flexible
##  [1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
## [15] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
## [29] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE

It seems that the pattern holds even with the flexible method, though the error rates in question are slightly lower across the board.

One final note on methods

All of the above assumed a fixed \(\sigma^2\) by arm - the ICC was varied just by changing \(\sigma^2_b\). Hence, we could use lme4 for this, and then extend to GLMMs instead of just LMMs using glmer. Alternatively, we can look at the impact of different \(\sigma^2\) values across arms.
